The paper deals with communication scenarios involving multiple terminals and non-additive channels, which are typical topics in the Information Theory (cs.IT) and Network Information Theory (cs.NI) sub-categories. The use of coset codes, which possess algebraic closure properties, is the main focus of the paper, making it relevant to the Coding Theory (cs.CC) sub-category. The three diverse communication scenarios considered in the paper - interference channel, broadcast channel, and multiple access with distributed states - are also relevant to the Signal Processing (cs.SI) and Multimedia (cs.MM) sub-categories.
